  pages = {265--273},
  publisher = {The Guilford Press},
  location = {New York, NY, US},
  abstract = {Emotions are dynamic, which means that no true understanding of emotion regulation is possible without understanding emotion regulation flexibility. A rapidly expanding body of work demonstrates that successful emotion regulation is flexible: Successful regulation draws from a wide repertoire, is responsive to feedback, and above all, is context sensitive. To continue building this work on a solid foundation, researchers need to integrate across flexibility dimensions, strategies, measures, and contexts, and to carefully separate capacity from tendency, and flexibility from instability. Flexibility requires variable responding. Thus, to understand flexible emotion regulation researchers must study how emotion regulation varies across time. Emotion regulation variability can be separated into within- and between-strategy variability. Within-strategy variability represents how the use of a single strategy varies across time. Our environment is in constant flux, and in response, our emotions change dynamically. Thus, when seeking to influence our emotions, one must also dynamically tune our emotion regulation efforts. This chapter discusses variability as a precursor to flexibility, introduces the components of emotion regulation flexibility, and finally discusses challenges and future research directions. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2024 APA, all rights reserved)},
